An immutable ledger is a type of database or record-keeping system where once data is written, it cannot be altered or deleted. This means that all transactions or changes made to the ledger are permanent and transparent, and can be traced back to their origin.

In the context of blockchain technology, immutability is a fundamental characteristic of the decentralized ledger that underpins the system. The blockchain is a distributed ledger where each block contains a set of transactions that have been verified and validated by network participants. Once a block is added to the blockchain, it cannot be modified or deleted without the consensus of the network participants. This ensures that the integrity of the blockchain is maintained and that all transactions are transparent and tamper-proof.

The immutability of the blockchain has several potential benefits, including increased transparency, security, and trust. Because the ledger cannot be altered or deleted, it is more difficult for bad actors to manipulate or corrupt the system. This makes the blockchain a useful tool for applications where the integrity of data is critical, such as supply chain management, voting systems, or financial transactions.

However, the immutability of the blockchain also has some potential drawbacks, such as the inability to correct errors or mistakes once they have been recorded on the ledger. This means that careful consideration must be given to the accuracy and completeness of data before it is added to the blockchain, and that mechanisms must be in place to address errors or discrepancies that are discovered after the fact.